Scenario 1: Multilinear Regression – Student Performance Prediction
Problem Statement

Predict student academic performance using academic, behavioral, and lifestyle factors.

 Dataset

Source: Kaggle

Link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/spscientist/students-performance-in-exams

 Target Variable

Final Exam Score
(Average of Math, Reading, and Writing scores)

Input Features

Study hours per day

Attendance percentage

Parental education level (encoded)

Test preparation course (encoded)

Sleep hours

 Methodology

Import required Python libraries

Load the student performance dataset

Preprocess data and encode categorical features

Compute the target variable

Handle missing values using imputation

Apply feature scaling

Split data into training and testing sets

Train a Multilinear Regression model

Predict student performance

Evaluate the model using:

Mean Squared Error (MSE)

Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)

R² Score

Analyze regression coefficients to understand feature influence

Optimize the model using:

Feature elimination

Ridge Regression

Lasso Regression

 Visualizations

Predicted vs Actual exam scores

Regression coefficient magnitude comparison

Residual distribution plot

 Scenario 2: Polynomial Regression – Vehicle Fuel Efficiency Prediction
 Problem Statement

Predict vehicle fuel efficiency (MPG) using engine horsepower, where the relationship is non-linear.

 Dataset

Source: Kaggle (UCI ML Repository)

Link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/uciml/autompg-dataset

 Target Variable

Miles Per Gallon (MPG)

Input Feature

Engine Horsepower

 Methodology

Import required Python libraries

Load and clean the Auto MPG dataset

Select horsepower as the independent variable

Handle missing values

Generate polynomial features (Degree 2, 3, and 4)

Apply feature scaling

Split the dataset into training and testing sets

Train Polynomial Regression models

Predict fuel efficiency values

Evaluate each model using:

Mean Squared Error (MSE)

Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)

R² Score

Compare performance across polynomial degrees

Apply Ridge Regression to reduce overfitting

 Visualizations

Polynomial curve fitting for different degrees

Training vs Testing error comparison

Overfitting and underfitting demonstration
